<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 42-year-old worker suffered burns and shock Wednesday when a tool he was 
using came in contact with a 12,000-volt power line at a parking garage 
construction site, the San Diego Fire Department reported. 
</P>
<P>
David Hernandez, of San Diegowas in guarded condition after undergoing surgery. 
He suffered third-degree burns on his neck, hands and upper body, UC San Diego 
Medical Center spokeswoman Barbara Brandt said. The 7 a.m. accident happened on 
the third level of a parking garage being built at 43rd and Meade streets. 
Hernandez was reportedly supporting a long, trowel-type tool, used in concrete 
work, on his neck and shoulders when it touched the power line. 
</P>
<P>
The state occupational safety agency was called in to investigate and all work 
was halted until the investigation is completed, a Fire Department spokesman 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
