<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Dana Parsons and Mark I. Pinsky 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TRAUMA TROUBLES: Orange County once had five trauma centers; with the closing 
of Fountain Valley Regional Hospital's center, it now has three (B1). . . . 
Since 1980, the centers have reduced the mortality rate in "preventable deaths" 
from 70% to under 5%, according to research by Dr. John G. West, a St. Joseph 
Hospital surgeon and trauma expert. . . . If another center closes, a potential 
disaster looms because of the domino effect on other aspects of medical care, 
West says, adding: "No way two trauma centers can do it." Dana Parsons and Mark 
I. Pinsky 
